# E2E Testing (Playwright)

Config: `playwright.config.ts` — base URL `http://localhost:5173`, 30s timeout.

## Structure

- `fixtures/` — page objects (`LandingPage`, `NavbarPage`, `ModalPage`, `SectionPage`); `test.ts` is the project's `test`/`expect` — **import from here, not `@playwright/test` directly**, so global setup (font mocking) applies everywhere
- `helpers/` — animation, screenshot, video, viewport, wait utilities
- `desktop/` and `mobile/` — spec files by viewport

## Font mocking

The site loads Nunito live from fonts.googleapis.com/fonts.gstatic.com with no caching. CI
fetching them fresh over the network on every run was the direct cause of recurring
low-percentage visual-regression pixel diffs. `fixtures/test.ts` intercepts those requests
and replays a cached response (`fixtures/font-cache/`) so every run renders byte-identical
fonts. Regenerate the cache after changing the Nunito `<link>` in `index.html`:

```bash
yarn test:e2e:update-font-cache
```

## Anti-flaky rules

**Do:** `expect().toBeVisible()`, `waitForLoadState`, helpers in `wait-helpers.ts` and `animation-helpers.ts`, semantic/`data-testid` locators.

**Don't:** `page.waitForTimeout()`, CSS-class-only selectors, test interdependencies, hard-coded delays.

## Stable assertions

1. **User-visible outcomes** — prefer `toBeVisible` / `toBeInViewport` / theme attribute / dialog open. Avoid asserting `hide`/`show`/`entrance` CSS classes except where that class is the public contract (then one test, not four).
2. **API-first** — use `scrollIntoViewIfNeeded` / `SectionPage.scrollToSection`, Swiper helpers (`swiperSlideNext(0)`, `getSwiperRealIndex`), video helpers (`ensureVideoPlaying`), `ModalPage` open/close. Do not use `waitForTimeout` to “settle.”
3. **Chromium-only for animation / pixel / exact-index** — keep `skipUnlessVisualBaseline` for screenshots; gate stagger/`animate__*`/threshold-pixel checks to Chromium, or delete tests that only sleep then assert visibility.

## Visual regression

- Visual baselines are **Chromium / Mobile Chrome** and **Linux-only** (`skipUnlessVisualBaseline` skips Darwin).
- Functional coverage still runs in Firefox, WebKit, and Mobile Safari.
- Prefer CSS/DOM assertions for hover and icon morph — do not screenshot hover states.
- Use `takeStableScreenshot` from `screenshot-helpers.ts` when adding new captures.
- Update Linux baselines after intentional UI changes:

```bash
yarn test:e2e:update-snapshots   # Docker → Linux *-linux.png (required for CI)
```

Snapshots live beside specs in `*-snapshots/` folders. Tolerant diff settings are in `playwright.config.ts`.
**Never rely on Darwin `--update-snapshots` to fix CI.** CI enforces this: a commit that changes
a `*-chromium-darwin.png`/`*-Mobile-Chrome-darwin.png` snapshot without its `*-linux.png`
sibling fails `scripts/check-visual-baseline-sync.mjs` (runs on both PRs and direct pushes to
`main` — this repo pushes straight to `main`, so the push-event path is the one that matters).

**The Linux baseline-generation container's OS must match the CI runner's OS.** Both
`scripts/update-e2e-snapshots.sh` and `scripts/run-e2e-ci-parity.sh` use the `-noble` (Ubuntu
24.04) Playwright image because GitHub's `ubuntu-latest` runner is Ubuntu 24.04. An earlier
version used `-jammy` (22.04) — two Ubuntu major versions ship different font/fontconfig
defaults, so baselines generated from jammy never matched CI and produced the *same* pixel
diff on every run (a real, deterministic environment mismatch, not flakiness). Verify with
`docker run --rm <image> cat /etc/os-release` before changing either script's image tag.

## Reproducing CI locally

`yarn test:e2e` on a Mac does not reproduce CI: different OS, different Chromium build (font
rendering, H.264 support), different `retries`/`workers` (CI-only via `CI=1` in
`playwright.config.ts`), no resource contention. Before pushing, run the same suite CI runs:

```bash
yarn test:e2e:ci-parity   # scripts/run-e2e-ci-parity.sh — noble container, CI=1, full suite
```

Set `CORP_CA_BUNDLE=<path-to-pem>` if behind a corporate TLS-intercepting proxy (same as
`test:e2e:update-snapshots`). Both container scripts mount an anonymous volume over
`node_modules` (`-v /work/node_modules`) — this repo uses yarn's `node-modules` linker, so
without that the container's `yarn install` writes Linux-native binaries (e.g.
`@rollup/rollup-linux-x64-gnu`) directly into the bind-mounted `node_modules` and breaks
`yarn test`/`yarn start` on the host until a fresh host-side `yarn install`.

## Known flakiness root causes (fixed) — don't reintroduce

History shows 9+ "fix e2e tests" commits that didn't stick because they treated symptoms.
Confirmed root causes and their permanent fixes, so future sessions don't have to
re-diagnose from scratch:

1. **Stale Linux baselines from the wrong container OS** — see "Visual regression" above.
2. **Date-driven layout drift** — `formatRoleDuration()` (`src/utils/durationUtils.ts`)
   renders tenure text from the real current date by default, so rendered text length (and
   therefore layout height) silently changes as real time passes, producing visual-regression
   diffs unrelated to any code change. `fixtures/test.ts` freezes `window.Date` to a fixed
   instant via `page.addInitScript` for every test — deliberately *not* using Playwright's
   `page.clock.install()`, which also fakes `requestAnimationFrame`/timers and would interfere
   with Swiper's ResizeObserver-driven settle logic and CSS transitions this suite already
   depends on.
3. **Modal open/close race under CPU contention** — `ModalPage.ts`'s retry-click loops
   (needed because a click can be lost or mistimed under the resource contention of CI's
   2-vCPU runner running 5 browser projects in parallel) had two bugs: `waitForModalOpen()`
   could re-click the trigger button even after the modal had already attached (a second
   `open()` call racing the lazy-mounted `ContactMeModal` chunk could toggle it closed again),
   and `closeByButton()` had no retry at all (unlike `closeByBackdrop()`, which already had
   one) — a single lost click meant a hard 10s timeout with no self-correction. This surfaced
   as different browsers failing on different runs (Firefox in some CI runs, WebKit when
   reproduced locally under `--cpus=2 --memory=4g` contention) — it was never actually
   browser-specific, just whichever engine happened to be slowest under contention that run.
   Verified fixed with 4 consecutive full-suite runs under contention showing zero modal
   failures (only the then-stale baseline diffs, since fixed separately).

## Swiper carousels

Use `swiperSlideNext`/`swiperSlidePrev` from `helpers/swiper-helpers.ts`, not raw
`el.swiper.slideNext()`. With `loop: true` + `autoHeight: true`, a `ResizeObserver` reacts
asynchronously to slide-height changes and recomputes the track position Swiper's index math
reads — firing nav calls back-to-back across separate `page.evaluate()` round-trips can race
that observer and silently no-op. The helpers wait for the wrapper's transform/height to
settle across two animation frames before and after each nav call.

## Commands

```bash
yarn test:e2e              # All E2E (Mac — fast sanity check, NOT a CI-equivalence check)
yarn test:e2e:ci-parity    # Full suite in a CI-equivalent container — run before pushing
yarn test:e2e:ui           # Interactive UI
npx playwright test --project=chromium
```

See `tests/e2e/README.md` for full guide.
